text: There are only two reasons I'm going to see this: I've obligated myself to watching every animated film that comes to theaters here and when the latest animated film is a musical, you'd better believe I'm gonna be there. (And yes, I've looked it up.  It is a musical) Not sure if I'll like it, though.  The reviews are certainly unfavorable beyond compare, which is a shame considering how long it took to make this (Though then again, Escape from Planet was apparently hell to get out to the public too and look how that turned out) but then again, I have found myself enjoying some films that get a lot of backlash from the public.  I'll also try judging it by its own merits.  That did help me get invested in Oz The Great and Powerful.  For all I know, it might be a pleasant surprise.  I've found going into a film with an open mind is much better than dwelling on what others have said about it, so I guess I'll have to judge it for myself when the time comes.

text: I respect any film getting made but one of the things that really makes this seem "cheap" is that every shot is locked off. I'm not saying I could pull this film off, but hear me out if you're trying to put your finger on what makes this "cheap".  Whoever was the Animation Director needs a shot of adrenaline.  Camera moves are about the easiest thing to add in these films once you've gone to the massive difficulty of creating and animating everyhting else.  Think how much more exciting the shot of Dorothy and the dog running towards the camera if the camera tracked backwards with them and down before the drawbridge slammed down just in front of the camera.  Instead, its glued to the ground and seems disinterested in events.  I've noticed this issue in other "cheap looking" animated films.
